onship]]\n|align=center |[[File:Keith Lee April 2018.jpg|100px]]\n|align=center | [[Keith Lee (wrestler)|Keith Lee]]\n|align=center | 1\n|align=center | January 22, 2020\n|align=center | {{age in days|month1=1|day1=22|year1=2020}}\n|align=center | [[Winter Park, Florida]]\n|Defeated [[Roderick Strong]] on ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]''.\n|-\n|align=center | [[NXT Tag Team Championship]]\n|align=center |[[File:Matt Riddle August 2017.jpg|100px]]<br>[[File:Pete Dunne.jpg|100px]]\n|align=center |The BroserWeights<br>{{small|([[Matt Riddle]] and [[Pete Dunne]])}}\n|align=center | 1\n|align=center | February 16, 2020\n|align=center | {{age in days|month1=2|day1=16|year1=2020}}\n|align=center | [[Portland, Oregon]]\n|Defeated [[The Undisputed Era]]'s [[Bobby Fish]] and [[Kyle O'Reilly]] at [[NXT TakeOver: Portland|TakeOver: Portland]].\n|}\n\n=== NXT UK ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%;\"\n|-\n!Championship\n!colspan=\"2\" | Current champion(s)\n!Reign\n!Date won\n!Days<br />held\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|align=center | [[NXT United Kingdom Championship]]\n|align=center | [[File:WALTER-PWG.jpg|100px]]\n|align=center | [[Walter (wrestler)|Walter]]\n|align=center | 1\n|align=center | April 5, 2019\n|align=center | {{age in days|month1=4|day1=5|year1=2019}}\n|align=center | [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|Defeated [[Pete Dunne (wrestler)|Pete Dunne]] at [[NXT TakeOver: New York|TakeOver: New York]].<br>{{small|Won the title as the WWE United Kingdom Championship.}}\n\n|-\n|align=center | [[NXT UK Women's Championship]]\n|align=center | [[file:Kay Lee Ray NXT UK Women's Champion.jpg|100px]]\n|align=center | [[Kay Lee Ray]]\n|align=center | 1\n|align=center | August 31, 2019\n|align=center | {{age in days|month1=8|day1=31|year1=2019}}\n|align=center | [[Cardiff, Wales]]\n|Defeated [[Toni Storm]] at [[NXT UK TakeOver: Cardiff|TakeOver: Cardiff]].\n|-\n|align=center | [[NXT UK Tag Team Championship]]\n|align=center | [[File:Wolfgang at Alpha-1 2019.jpg|100px]]\n|align=center | Gallus<br>{{small|([[Mark Coffey]] and [[Wolfgang (wrestler)|Wolfgang]] (pictured))}}\n|align=center | 1\n|align=center | October 4, 2019\n|align=center | {{age in days|month1=10|day1=4|year1=2019}}\n|align=center | [[Brentwood, England]]\n|Defeated [[Flash Morgan Webster|\"Flash\" Morgan Webster]] and [[Mark Andrews (wrestler)|Mark Andrews]] on ''[[NXT UK]]''.<br><small>Aired on [[Broadcast delay|tape delay]] on October 17, 2019.<br/></small>\n|}\n\n=== Shared titles ===\n:The NXT Cruiserweight Championship is shared between NXT, NXT UK, and 205 Live \n:The 24/7 Championship is shared between all five brands\n:The Women's Tag Team Championship is shared between Raw, SmackDown, and NXT. \n\nThe colors indicate the home brand of the champions.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: auto\"\n|-\n|style=\"background:#FBB; width:2em\"|\n|[[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]]\n|style=\"background:#BBF; width:2em\"|\n|[[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]]\n|style=\"background:yellow; width:2em\"|\n|[[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]]\n|style=\"background:#EEE8AA; width:2em\"|\n|[[NXT UK (WWE brand)|NXT UK]]\n|style=\"background:#E0CEF2; width:2em\"|\n|[[205 Live (WWE brand)|205 Live]]\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%;\"\n|-\n!Championship\n!colspan=\"2\" | Current champion(s)\n!Reign\n!Date won\n!Days<br />held\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[NXT Cruiserweight Championship]]\n|align=center | [[File:2018-01-20 21-11-56 ILCE-6500 DSC04423 (24958700327).jpg|100px]]\n|style=\"background-color: #EEE8AA;\" columnspan=1 align=\"center\"|[[Jordan Devlin]]\n|align=center | 1\n|align=center | January 25, 2020\n|align=center | {{age in days|month1=1|day1=25|year1=2020}}\n|align=center | [[Houston, Texas]]\n|Defeated former champion [[Angel Garza]], [[Travis Banks]], and [[Isaiah \"Swerve\" Scott]], who Devlin pinned, in a [[fatal four-way match]] at [[Worlds Collide (2020)|Worlds Collide]].\n|-\n|[[WWE 24/7 Championship|24/7 Championship]]\n|align=center | [[File:Mojo Rawley in December 2016.jpg|100px]]\n|style=\"background-color: #BBF;\" columnspan=1 align=\"center\"|[[Mojo Rawley]]\n|align=center | 7\n|align=center | March 25, 2020\n|align=center | {{age in days|month1=3|day=25|year1=2020}}\n|align=center | [[Orlando, Florida]]\n|Pinned [[R-Truth]] on a pillar at night one of [[WrestleMania 36]].<br><small>Aired on [[tape delay]] on April 4, 2020.</br>\n|-\n|[[WWE Women's Tag Team Championship|Women's Tag Team Championship]]\n|align=center | [[File:August52019pittsburgh.jpg|100px]]\n|style=\"background-color: #BBF;\" columnspan=1 align=\"center\"|[[Alexa Bliss]] and [[Nikki Cross]]\n|align=center | 2\n|align=center | March 25, 2020\n|align=center | {{age in days|month1=3|day1=25|year1=2020}}\n|align=center | [[Orlando, Florida]]\n|Defeated The Kabuki Warriors ([[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]] and [[Kairi Sane]]) on night one of [[WrestleMania 36]].<br><small>Aired on [[tape delay]] on April 4, 2020.</br>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Grand Slam (professional wrestling)#WWE (1997)|WWE Grand Slam]]\n*[[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#WWE|WWE Triple Crown]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.wwe.com/ WWE.com]\n{{WWE Championships}}\n{{WWE}}\n\n[[Category:WWE championships lists]]\n", "name_user": "WrestlerHelper3", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSmackDown", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_current_champions_in_WWE"}
{"title_page": "Beatrice Ancillotti Goretti", "text_new": "{{original research|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Beatrice Ancillotti Goretti\n| image       = Beatrice Ancilotti Goretti.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = Self-portrait of Beatrice Ancillotti Goretti\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 1879\n| birth_place = [[Florence]]\n| death_date  = 1937\n| death_place = [[Pistoia]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| term        =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| party       =\n| boards      =\n| religion    =\n| spouse      =\n| partner     =\n| children    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[Italy|Italian]]\n}}\n'''Beatrice Ancillotti Goretti''' (1879\u20131937) was an Italian artist who painted in the [[Renaissance art|Renaissance]] tradition.\n\n==Family ==\nBeatrice Caterina Enrichetta Ancillotti Goretti was born in [[Florence]] in 1879 into a family of impassioned liberals. Her maternal grandfather Demetrio Corgialegno (1785\u20131861), who had settled in Florence, came from an old and rich [[Byzantine]] noble family. He fought alongside the poet, [[Lord Byron|Lord George Byron]], during the Greek war of independence. He established a secret organisation aimed at overthrowing [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule based in both [[Corfu]] and his home town, Argostoli. Later, between 1838 and 1842, owing to his Tuscan connections, the Grand Duke of Tuscany, [[Grand duke of Tuscany Leopold II|Leopoldo II]], gifted to him large quantities of books for the newly founded [[University of Athens]].<ref name=\"Delcorno Giovanna\">{{cite book|last=Delcorno|first=Giovanna|title=Maria Sara Goretti, la sua vita, i suoi libri|year=2005|publisher=L'Archiginnsio|pages=519\u2013540}}</ref>\n\nIn 1871 Goretti's future father, Torello Ancillotti (1843\u20131899)  married her mother Marianna Coriaglegno,<ref>{{cite web |title=Torello Ancillotti |url=http://www.enricogallerie.com/artista/ancillotti-torello-653.asp |website=enricogallerie.com}}</ref>  known in the family as Demetria or Memi, with whom he would have two other children,  Luisa, who died aged nine,  and Demetrio apart from Beatrice. Torello Ancillotti  had met his wife through his friend and the son of Demetrio Corgialegno, Carlo, when, in 1859, they had both joined [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] during Italy's [[Third Italian War of Independence|Third War of Independence]]. Awarded a silver medal for bravery during the conflict, when he returned to Florence, he was employed by  the National Library of Florence. As a youth, he had studied at both the [[Accademia di Belle Arti di Firenze]] and that of Siena. He continued to paint, influenced greatly by the  [[Macchiaioli]], and in 1876 and 1877 held exhibitions in both Genoa and Turin.<ref name=\"Maria Goretti\">{{cite book|last=Goretti|first=Maria|title=Omaggio a Torello Ancillotti|year=1989|publisher=Pizzoli|location=Bologna}}</ref>\n\nLeaving his family behind in Florence, in 1877, Torello Ancillotti moved to Rouen in France where, during a liaison with the Countess of Barr, he began an intense and successful period of artistic activity as a painter, water colourist and sculptor. \n\n==Relationship with painter Giovanni Costetti==\nFollowing in her father's footsteps, Goretti attended the Accademia di Belle Arti in Florence before taking advanced classes at [[Giovanni Fattori]]'s Free School of the Nude. It was there that she probably met and started a love affair with fellow student and artist, Giovanni Costetti (1878\u20131949).<ref>{{cite web |title=Biblioteca delle Signorine Salani |url=http://www.letteraturadimenticata.it/Illustratori%20Signorine.htm |website=letteraturadimenticata.it}}</ref>  He painted a portrait of her entitled ''The Good Smile''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uffizi.firenze.it/musei/?m=artemoderna |title=Polo Museale Fiorentino :: Sito Ufficiale |work=uffizi.firenze.it |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329071646/http://www.uffizi.firenze.it/musei/?m=artemoderna |archivedate=2014-03-29 }}</ref>  found in the Modern Art Gallery of the Pitti Palace in Florence. In 1899, she also painted a portrait of him that hangs in the same gallery.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nIn 1901, both artists took part in the 1901 Alinari Divine Comedy Competition, which involved preparing new illustrations for [[Dante]]'s epic poem ''[[The Divine Comedy]]''.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nIn 1903 Cosetti challenged a rival artist, [[Augusto Mussini]] (1870\u20131919) to a duel because he had become infatuated with Goretti. When Mussini disappeared from the city, he was feared dead. Instead, he had escaped from Florence to take refuge in a monastery in the north of Italy where he became a monk, although he never pronounced his final vows.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://giornale.regione.marche.it/archivio/num10_11_1205/artcom22.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516033239/http://giornale.regione.marche.it/archivio/num10_11_1205/artcom22.htm |archive-date=2006-05-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Costetti reported two of Goretti's aunts to the police accusing them of keeping her a recluse. Before leaving Florence after she had ended the affair, she made a statement before a public notary in which she said she had, of her own free will, refused to marry Costetti and strongly denied the rumor that she had been forced into seclusion by her relatives declaring \"I am an adult and no one can impose their will on me\".<ref name=\"Delcorno Giovanna\" />\n\n==Artistic legacy==\nFollowing her departure from Florence, she settled at Stellata, in the [[province of Ferrara]]. Here she met Andrea Goretti, whom she married in Fiesole soon after, on 22 February 1904. This was the same year she painted her ''Self Portrait''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumsinflorence.com/musei/gallery_of_modern_art.html|title=Gallery of Modern Art \u2013 Florence|work=museumsinflorence.com}}</ref> which is amongst the 170 watercolors, pastels, and pencil drawings  bequeathed by her only daughter Maria Sara Goretti<ref name=\"badigit.comune.bologna.it\">[http://badigit.comune.bologna.it/fondi/fondi/ISAAR_Goretti.htm Goretti], comune.bologna.it, Retrieved 2016</ref> to the Modern Art Collection.<ref name=\"FortuneFalcone2010\">{{cite book|author1=Jane Fortune|author2=Linda Falcone|title=Invisibile women. Forgotten artist of Florence. Ediz. italiana e inglese|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n-ujfOEWcfcC&pg=PA197|year=2010|publisher=TheFlorentinePress|isbn=978-88-902434-5-5|pages=197\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Additional vocations==\nDuring [[World War I]] she worked as a nurse tending the wounded and the dying; that in 1925, she became a [[Quaker]] entering the Society of Friends of London; and that, in 1932, she was a registered member of the Italian Trade Union of  Women Professional Artists.<ref name=\"Delcorno Giovanna\" />\n\nIn 1937 Goretti, aged 58, died in [[Pistoia]], a town about 35 kilometers north west of Florence.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Giovanna Delcorno, Maria Sara Goretti, la sua vita, i suoi libri, \u00abL'Archiginnasio\u00bb, C (2005), pp.&nbsp;519\u2013540\n*Patrizia Busi, Le carte di Maria Sara Goretti, \u00abL'Archiginnasio\u00bb, C (2005), pp.&nbsp;541\u2013566.\n*Giovanna Delcorno and Patrizia Busi, Aeropoesia futurista e pedagogia : i libri e le carte di Maria Sara Goretti alla Biblioteca dell'Archiginnasio, [S.l.: s.n., 2005?], pp.&nbsp;520\u2013566 : ill.; 24&nbsp;cm. (Estr. da: L'Archiginnsio, 100 (2005)\n*Jane Fortune, Invisible Women: Forgotten Artists of Florence, Florence, The Florentine Press, 2009, {{ISBN|978-88-902434-5-5}}\n*Maddalena Paola Winspeare, Donne & Colori: Artiste Nei Musei Statali Fiorentini \u2013 Women & Colours Women Artists in the Florentine State Museums, 2002,  Sillabe, 2002, {{ISBN|9788883471100}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goretti, Beatrice Ancillotti}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian women painters]]\n[[Category:People from Florence]]\n[[Category:19th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{original research|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Beatrice Ancillotti Goretti\n| image       = Beatrice Ancilotti Goretti.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = Self-portrait of Beatrice Ancillotti Goretti\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 1879\n| birth_place = [[Florence]]\n| death_date  = 1937\n| death_place = [[Pistoia]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| term        =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| party       =\n| boards      =\n| religion    =\n| spouse      =\n| partner     =\n| children    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[Italy|Italian]]\n}}\n'''Beatrice Ancillotti Goretti''' (1879\u20131937) was an Italian artist who painted in the [[Renaissance art|Renaissance]] tradition.\n\n==Family ==\nBeatrice Caterina Enrichetta Ancillotti Goretti was born in [[Florence]] in 1879 into a family of impassioned liberals. Her maternal grandfather Demetrio Corgialegno (1785\u20131861), who had settled in Florence, came from an old and rich [[Byzantine]] noble family. He fought alongside the poet, [[Lord Byron|Lord George Byron]], during the Greek war of independence. He established a secret organisation aimed at overthrowing [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule based in both [[Corfu]] and his home town, Argostoli. Later, between 1838 and 1842, owing to his Tuscan connections, the Grand Duke of Tuscany, [[Grand duke of Tuscany Leopold II|Leopoldo II]], gifted to him large quantities of books for the newly founded [[University of Athens]].<ref name=\"Delcorno Giovanna\">{{cite book|last=Delcorno|first=Giovanna|title=Maria Sara Goretti, la sua vita, i suoi libri|year=2005|publisher=L'Archiginnsio|pages=519\u2013540}}</ref>\n\nIn 1871 Goretti's future father, Torello Ancillotti (1843\u20131899)  married her mother Marianna Coriaglegno,<ref>{{cite web |title=Torello Ancillotti |url=http://www.enricogallerie.com/artista/ancillotti-torello-653.asp |website=enricogallerie.com}}</ref>  known in the family as Demetria or Memi, with whom he would have two other children,  Luisa, who died aged nine,  and Demetrio apart from Beatrice. Torello Ancillotti  had met his wife through his friend and the son of Demetrio Corgialegno, Carlo, when, in 1859, they had both joined [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] during Italy's [[Third Italian War of Independence|Third War of Independence]]. Awarded a silver medal for bravery during the conflict, when he returned to Florence, he was employed by  the National Library of Florence. As a youth he had studied at both the [[Accademia di Belle Arti di Firenze]] and that of Siena. He continued to paint, influenced greatly by the  [[Macchiaioli]], and in 1876 and 1877 held exhibitions in both Genoa and Turin.<ref name=\"Maria Goretti\">{{cite book|last=Goretti|first=Maria|title=Omaggio a Torello Ancillotti|year=1989|publisher=Pizzoli|location=Bologna}}</ref>\n\nLeaving his family behind in Florence, in 1877, Torello Ancillotti moved to Rouen in France where, during a liaison with the Countess of Barr, he began an intense and successful period of artistic activity as a painter, water colourist and sculptor. \n\n==Relationship with painter Giovanni Costetti==\nFollowing in her father's footsteps, Goretti attended the Accademia di Belle Arti in Florence before taking advanced classes at [[Giovanni Fattori]]'s Free School of the Nude. It was there that she probably met and started a love affair with fellow student and artist, Giovanni Costetti (1878\u20131949).<ref>{{cite web |title=Biblioteca delle Signorine Salani |url=http://www.letteraturadimenticata.it/Illustratori%20Signorine.htm |website=letteraturadimenticata.it}}</ref>  He painted a portrait of her entitled ''The Good Smile''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uffizi.firenze.it/musei/?m=artemoderna |title=Polo Museale Fiorentino :: Sito Ufficiale |work=uffizi.firenze.it |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329071646/http://www.uffizi.firenze.it/musei/?m=artemoderna |archivedate=2014-03-29 }}</ref>  found in the Modern Art Gallery of the Pitti Palace in Florence. In 1899, she also painted a portrait of him that hangs in the same gallery.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nIn 1901, both artists took part in the 1901 Alinari Divine Comedy Competition which involved preparing new illustrations for [[Dante]]'s epic poem ''[[The Divine Comedy]]''.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nIn 1903 Cosetti challenged a rival artist, [[Augusto Mussini]] (1870\u20131919) to a duel because he had become infatuated with Goretti. When Mussini disappeared from the city, he was feared dead. Instead, he had escaped from Florence to take refuge in a monastery in the north of Italy where he became a monk, although he never pronounced his final vows.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://giornale.regione.marche.it/archivio/num10_11_1205/artcom22.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516033239/http://giornale.regione.marche.it/archivio/num10_11_1205/artcom22.htm |archive-date=2006-05-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Costetti reported two of Goretti's aunts to the police accusing them of keeping her a recluse. Before leaving Florence after she had ended the affair, she made a statement before a public notary in which she said she had, of her own free will, refused to marry Costetti and strongly denied the rumor that she had been forced into seclusion by her relatives declaring \"I am an adult and no one can impose their will on me\".<ref name=\"Delcorno Giovanna\" />\n\n==Artistic legacy==\nFollowing her departure from Florence, she settled at Stellata, in the [[province of Ferrara]]. Here she met Andrea Goretti, whom she married in Fiesole soon after, on 22 February 1904. This was the same year she painted her ''Self Portrait''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumsinflorence.com/musei/gallery_of_modern_art.html|title=Gallery of Modern Art \u2013 Florence|work=museumsinflorence.com}}</ref> which is amongst the 170 watercolors, pastels, and pencil drawings  bequeathed by her only daughter Maria Sara Goretti<ref name=\"badigit.comune.bologna.it\">[http://badigit.comune.bologna.it/fondi/fondi/ISAAR_Goretti.htm Goretti], comune.bologna.it, Retrieved 2016</ref> to the Modern Art Collection.<ref name=\"FortuneFalcone2010\">{{cite book|author1=Jane Fortune|author2=Linda Falcone|title=Invisibile women. Forgotten artist of Florence. Ediz. italiana e inglese|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n-ujfOEWcfcC&pg=PA197|year=2010|publisher=TheFlorentinePress|isbn=978-88-902434-5-5|pages=197\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Additional vocations==\nDuring [[World War I]] she worked as a nurse tending the wounded and the dying; that in 1925, she became a [[Quaker]] entering the Society of Friends of London; and that, in 1932, she was a registered member of the Italian Trade Union of  Women Professional Artists.<ref name=\"Delcorno Giovanna\" />\n\nIn 1937 Goretti, aged 58, died in [[Pistoia]], a town about 35 kilometers north west of Florence.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Giovanna Delcorno, Maria Sara Goretti, la sua vita, i suoi libri, \u00abL'Archiginnasio\u00bb, C (2005), pp.&nbsp;519\u2013540\n*Patrizia Busi, Le carte di Maria Sara Goretti, \u00abL'Archiginnasio\u00bb, C (2005), pp.&nbsp;541\u2013566.\n*Giovanna Delcorno and Patrizia Busi, Aeropoesia futurista e pedagogia : i libri e le carte di Maria Sara Goretti alla Biblioteca dell'Archiginnasio, [S.l.: s.n., 2005?], pp.&nbsp;520\u2013566 : ill.; 24&nbsp;cm. (Estr. da: L'Archiginnsio, 100 (2005)\n*Jane Fortune, Invisible Women: Forgotten Artists of Florence, Florence, The Florentine Press, 2009, {{ISBN|978-88-902434-5-5}}\n*Maddalena Paola Winspeare, Donne & Colori: Artiste Nei Musei Statali Fiorentini \u2013 Women & Colours Women Artists in the Florentine State Museums, 2002,  Sillabe, 2002, {{ISBN|9788883471100}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goretti, Beatrice Ancillotti}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian women painters]]\n[[Category:People from Florence]]\n[[Category:19th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century women artists]]\n", "name_user": "Resowithrae", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a comma after youth", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beatrice_Ancillotti_Goretti"}
{"title_page": "Gun laws in Nevada", "text_new": "[[File:Map of USA NV.svg|thumb|Location of Nevada in the United States]]\n'''Gun laws in Nevada''' regulate the sale, possession, and use of [[firearm]]s and [[ammunition]] in the state of [[Nevada]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/state-gun-laws/nevada/ | title=Nevada Gun Laws | publisher=National Rifle Association \u2013 Institute for Legislative Action | access-date=2020-04-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://lawcenter.giffords.org/gun-laws/state-law/nevada/ | title=Nevada Gun Laws | publisher=Giffords Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence | access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==Summary table==\n<!-- Transcludes to [[Gun laws in the United States by state]] --><onlyinclude>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%; width:95%;\"\n|-\n! Subject/Law !! Long guns!! Handguns !! Relevant statutes !! Notes\n|-\n| State permit required to purchase? || No || No ||  || \n|-\n| Firearm registration? || No || No || || As of June 2015, Clark County no longer requires the registration of handguns. There is now state preemption for firearm registration.<ref>{{cite news |first=Colton |last=Lochhead |date=June 11, 2015 |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/las-vegas/what-happens-firearm-blue-cards-now-state-controls-registration |title=What Happens to Firearm 'Blue Cards' Now that State Controls Registration? |newspaper=Las Vegas Review-Journal |access-date=November 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Owner license required? || No || No ||  ||\n|-\n| Permit required for concealed carry? || N/A || Yes || [http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-202.html#NRS202Sec3657 NRS 202\u00a73657 - Application and Permitting][http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-202.html#NRS202Sec360 NRS 202\u00a7360 - Prohibited Persons]|| Nevada is a \"shall issue\" state for concealed carry.\n|-\n| Permit required for open carry? || No || No || [http://www.leg.state.nv.us/const/nvconst.html#Art1Sec11 NV Constitution Article 1 Section 11][http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-503.html#NRS503Sec165 NRS 503\u00a7165 - Carrying loaded rifle or shotgun in or on vehicle on or along public way unlawful; exceptions.]|| Open carry is generally permitted throughout the state. For open carry in a vehicle, the firearm may be anywhere except concealed upon the person without a concealed firearm permit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.municode.com/HTML/16023/level2/TIT9PUPEMOWE_CH9.32WEGE.html#TIT9PUPEMOWE_CH9.32WEGE_9.32.080DEWEPRVEXC |title=North Las Vegas Municipal Ord. 9\u00a732.080 - Deadly weapon prohibited in vehicle \u2014 Exceptions |publisher=Municode.com |accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.municode.com/HTML/16023/level2/TIT9PUPEMOWE_CH9.32WEGE.html#TIT9PUPEMOWE_CH9.32WEGE_9.32.040DADEWEDE |title=North Las Vegas Municipal Ord. 9\u00a732.040 - Dangerous or Deadly Weapon defined |publisher=Municode.com |accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| State preemption of local restrictions? || Yes || Yes || [http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-244.html#NRS244Sec364 NRS 244\u00a7364 - County of 700,000 or more][http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-268.html#NRS268Sec418 NRS\u2002268\u00a7418 - City of 700,000 or more][http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-269.html#NRS269Sec222 NRS 269\u00a7222 - Town of 700,000 or more]|| Local authorities may regulate the discharge of firearms. Handgun registration in Clark County was grandfathered in, until SB175 (signed into law June 2nd, 2015) removed the authority of the county to register handguns in Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/78th2015/Reports/history.cfm?ID=399 |title=SB175|website=Leg.state.nv.us|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> \n|-\n| Assault weapon law? || No || No ||  || \n|-\n| Magazine Capacity Restriction? || No || No || || \n|- \n| NFA weapons restricted? || No || No || [http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-202.html#NRS202Sec275 NRS\u2002202\u00a7275\u2002\u2002Possession, manufacture or disposition of short-barreled rifle or short-barreled shotgun][http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-202.html#NRS202Sec350 NRS\u2002202\u00a7350\u2002\u2002Manufacture, importation, possession or use of dangerous weapon or silencer][http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/USCODE-2010-title18/html/USCODE-2010-title18-partI-chap44-sec922.htm 18 USC \u00a7922(b)4 - Unlawful Transfer][http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CFR-2012-title27-vol3/xml/CFR-2012-title27-vol3-part478.xml#seqnum478.98 27 CFR \u00a7478.98 - Sales or deliveries of destructive devices and certain firearms.]|| Possession and ownership of an SBR, SBS, machine gun (selective-fire weapon), or silencer, all NFA items, are subject to federal purview and regulation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/USCODE-2010-title18/html/USCODE-2010-title18-partI-chap44-sec922.htm |title=18 USC \u00a7922(b)4 - Unlawful Transfer |publisher=GPO.gov |date=April 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CFR-2012-title27-vol3/xml/CFR-2012-title27-vol3-part478.xml#seqnum478.98 |title=27 CFR \u00a7478.98 - Sales or deliveries of destructive devices and certain firearms. |publisher=GPO.gov |date=April 1, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| Background checks required for private sales? || Yes || Yes ||  || In November 2016, Nevada voters approved Ballot Question 1, changing the law to require background checks for private sales.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ric |last=Anderson |date=November 9, 2016 |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2016/nov/09/ballot-question-closing-background-check-loophole/ |title=Ballot Question Closing Background Check Loophole Passes in Nevada |newspaper=Las Vegas Sun |access-date=November 9, 2016 |quote=The measure makes private transactions subject to the same legal requirement as purchases involving licensed dealers, for which federal background checks are necessary.}}</ref> Nevada Attorney General [[Adam Laxalt]] opined that the law is unenforceable.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nraila.org/articles/20161228/nevada-attorney-general-says-question-one-background-check-law-unenforceable|title=NRA-ILA {{!}} Nevada Attorney General Says Question One Background Check Law 'Unenforceable'|last=NRA-ILA|newspaper=NRA-ILA|access-date=2017-01-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ag.nv.gov/uploadedFiles/agnvgov/Content/Publications/AGO_2016-12.pdf|title=AG Opinion|last=|first=|date=|website=Ag.nv.gov|access-date=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nA revised version was signed into law on February 15, 2019 to fix the deficiencies of Question 1. The law is set to go into effect in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nraila.org/articles/20190215/nevada-governor-signs-bloomberg-background-check-bill-criminalizing-private-firearm-transfers|title=NRA-ILA {{!}} Nevada: Governor Signs Bloomberg Background Check Bill Criminalizing Private Firearm Transfers|last=NRA-ILA|website=NRA-ILA|language=en|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Bill |last=Dentzer |date=February 15, 2019 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/2019-legislature/sisolak-signs-nevada-gun-background-checks-bill-into-law-1598362/ |title=Sisolak Signs Nevada Gun Background Checks Bill into Law |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome local counties have adopted [[Second Amendment sanctuary]] resolutions in opposition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/nevada/4-nevada-counties-join-second-amendment-sanctuary-drive-1624255/|title=4 Nevada counties join \u2018Second Amendment sanctuary\u2019 drive|date=2019-03-22|website=Las Vegas Review-Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref>\n|-\n|Red flag law?\n|Yes\n|Yes\n|\n|Police may confiscate firearms from those considered a threat.<ref name=\"AB291\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/2019-legislature/nevada-gov-sisolak-signs-gun-control-bill-into-law-1687293/|title=Nevada Gov. Sisolak signs gun control bill into law|date=2019-06-14|website=Las Vegas Review-Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n|}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Concealed carry==\nNevada is a \"shall issue\" state for [[concealed carry]]. The county sheriff shall issue a concealed firearms permit to applicants who qualify under state and federal law, who submit an application in accordance with the provisions of section NRS 202.3657.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-202.html#NRS202Sec3657 |title=NRS\u2002202.3657\u2002\u2002Application for permit; eligibility; denial or revocation of permit. |publisher=LEG.state.NV.US |accessdate=April 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-202.html#NRS202Sec360 |title=NRS\u2002202.360\u2002\u2002Ownership or possession of firearm by certain persons prohibited; penalties. |publisher=LEG.state.NV.US |accessdate=April 28, 2013}}</ref> To apply for a Concealed Firearm Permit, a person must be 21 (18 for military),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/nevada/articles/2017-05-22/nevada-permits-young-soldiers-to-carry-concealed-weapons|title=Nevada Permits Young Soldiers to Carry Concealed Weapons|website=Usnews.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002220044/https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/nevada/articles/2017-05-22/nevada-permits-young-soldiers-to-carry-concealed-weapons|archive-date=2017-10-02|url-status=dead|access-date=2 October 2017}}</ref> complete an approved course in firearm safety and demonstrate competence (qualify) with any handgun. Previously, a single permit applied to only those firearms the applicant qualified with. Under revised legislation, a single permit is valid for all handguns the person owns or may thereafter own.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-202.html#NRS202Sec3657 |title=NRS\u2002202.3657\u2002-\u2002Application for permit; eligibility; denial or revocation of permit. |publisher=LEG.state.NV.US |accessdate=April 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/Statutes/77th2013/Stats201307.html#Stats201307page1139 |title=2013 Statutes of Nevada, Page 1139 (Chapter 255, SB 76) |publisher=LEG.state.NV.US |accessdate=April 28, 2013}}</ref> Holders of previous permit iterations are grandfathered per current law and are no longer constrained to their qualified firearms, nor qualified firearm action.\n\nNote: The change in the law regarding competence with semi-automatic handguns is effective July 1, 2011 through Nevada Assembly Bill AB 282.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/76th2011/Reports/history.cfm?ID=597 |title=AB282 |publisher=Leg.state.nv.us |accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref> This change is retroactive meaning that permits issued prior to July 1, 2011, that have specific semiautomatic firearms listed is the equivalent to having all semiautomatic firearms authorized.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/76th2011/Minutes/Assembly/JUD/Final/603.pdf|format=PDF|title=MINUTES OF THE MEETING OF THE ASSEMBLY COMMITTEE ON JUDICIARY : Seventy-Sixth Session|date=March 30, 2011|website=Leg.state.nv.us|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nStates that honor a Nevada permit: Alaska, Arizona, Iowa, Idaho, Indiana, Kansas*, Kentucky, Louisiana, Michigan*, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, Oklahoma, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Utah (*Residential permits only).\n\n{{As of|2016|07|01}}, other state permits that Nevada honors: Alaska, Arizona, Arkansas, Florida, Idaho Enhanced Permit, Illinois, Kansas, Kentucky, Louisiana, Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota, Mississippi Enhanced Permit, Montana, Nebraska, New Mexico, North Carolina, North Dakota (both types of permits), Ohio, Oklahoma, South Carolina, South Dakota Enhanced Permit, Tennessee, Texas, Utah, Virginia, West Virginia, Wisconsin, Wyoming.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gsd.nv.gov/uploadedFiles/gsdnvgov/content/Resources/Final%20state%20list%20posted%207-2-16.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129223436/http://gsd.nv.gov/uploadedFiles/gsdnvgov/content/Resources/Final%20state%20list%20posted%207-2-16.pdf |archivedate=2016-11-29 }}</ref> The law allows holders of valid permits from these states to carry a concealed weapon while in the State of Nevada. The valid permit along with current photo I.D. must be in the possession of the person at all times while carrying a concealed firearm.\n\nOn February 28, 2013, the Nevada Sheriffs' and Chiefs' association voted unanimously to end the recognition of Arizona concealed weapon permits.\n\nEffective June 23, 2015 Nevada once again recognizes Arizona concealed weapon permits.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gsd.nv.gov/uploadedFiles/gsdnvgov/content/Resources/Revised%20CCW%20adding%20SD%2010-12-15%20(2).pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-10-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123015010/http://gsd.nv.gov/uploadedFiles/gsdnvgov/content/Resources/Revised%20CCW%20adding%20SD%2010-12-15%20(2).pdf |archivedate=2015-11-23 }}</ref> \n\nThe concealed firearm permit cost differs depending on which county one applies in. The application must be turned in to the county in which the applicant resides. The permit is valid for five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRs/NRS-202.html#NRS202Sec366|title=NRS: CHAPTER 202 - CRIMES AGAINST PUBLIC HEALTH AND SAFETY|website=Leg.state.nv.us|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Open carry==\nNevada is a traditional [[open carry]] state with complete state preemption of firearms laws. Effective June 2, 2016 SB 175<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leg.state.nv.us/App/NELIS/REL/78th2015/Bill/1548/Overview|title=SB175  Overview|website=leg.state.nv.us|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> and SB 240<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/78th2015/Reports/history.cfm?billname=SB240|title=SB240|website=Leg.state.nv.us|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> (duplicate provisions) is legislation that prohibits counties, cities, and towns from enacting ordinances more restrictive than state law.  The legislature reserves for itself the right to legislate all areas of firearm law except unsafe discharge of firearms.\n\n{{quote box |quote  = The regulation of the transfer, sale, purchase, possession, carrying, ownership, transportation, storage, registration and licensing of firearms, firearm accessories and ammunition in this State and the ability to define such terms is within the exclusive domain of the Legislature, and any other law, regulation, rule or ordinance to the contrary is null and void. \n |author = \u2014[https://www.leg.state.nv.us/nrs/NRS-244.html#NRS244Sec364 NRS 244.364]\n |source = Taken from text of SB 240.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/78th2015/Bills/SB/SB240_EN.pdf|format=PDF|title=Senate Bill No. 240|website=Leg.state.nv.us|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n |width  = 50%\n |align  = right\n}}\n\n==Registration of firearms==\nNevada state law does not require the registration of firearms. Following the passage of SB 175, handgun registration (or registration of any kind), is no longer required in Clark County or anywhere in the state of Nevada for handguns or long-arms (which already did not require registration). Governor [[Brian Sandoval]] signed this bill into law on June 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nevadacarry.org/blue-cards|title=Blue Cards|website=Nevada Carry|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other laws==\nAB 217, allows residents of non-contiguous states to purchase long guns in Nevada.  It also allows Nevada residents to purchase long guns in non-contiguous states.  This legislation brings Nevada in line with the protections provided by the Firearms Owners Protection Act, which allows for the interstate sale of long guns by federally licensed firearms dealers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/NV/bill/AB217/2011|title=Nevada AB217 {{!}} 2011 {{!}} 76th Legislature|website=LegiScan|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\nAB 282 ensures that concealed firearm permit holders' names and addresses remain confidential; revise Nevada state law to allow carrying of any semi-automatic pistol, as with revolvers, once qualified for a CCW permit with a semi-automatic pistol; allows carrying of firearms in Nevada state parks; and statutorily mandates a background investigation (which is currently being done by all Nevada sheriffs) for CCW permit renewals for the purpose of reinstating the National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS) exemption for Nevada, thus ensuring that permit holders do not have to go through a point-of-contact check for every firearm purchased, as long as the CCW permit is valid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/NV/bill/AB282/2011|title=Nevada AB282 {{!}} 2011 {{!}} 76th Legislature|website=LegiScan|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\nAB 291 bans [[Bump fire|bump stocks]], enacts a [[red flag law]], and requires safe storage of firearms.<ref name=\"AB291\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Gun laws in the United States (by state)}}\n\n[[Category:Nevada law]]\n[[Category:United States gun laws by state|Nevada]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Map of USA NV.svg|thumb|Location of Nevada in the United States]]\n'''Gun laws in Nevada''' regulate the sale, possession, and use of [[firearm]]s and [[ammunition]] in the state of [[Nevada]] in the United States.<ref>[http://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/state-laws/nevada.aspx \"State Gun Laws: Nevada\"], National Rifle Association \u2013 Institute for Legislative Action. Retrieved December 31, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://smartgunlaws.org/nevada-state-law-summary/ \"Nevada State Law Summary\"], Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence. Retrieved December 31, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Summary table==\n<!-- Transcludes to [[Gun laws in the United States by state]] --><onlyinclude>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%; width:95%;\"\n|-\n! Subject/Law !! Long guns!! Handguns !!